  "text": "The Rust borrow checker MIR analysis chain traces through the NLL (Non-Lexical Lifetimes) infrastructure in rustc. The process begins at the query entry point `mir_borrowck` (compiler/rustc_borrowck/src/lib.rs:117), which creates a `BorrowCheckRootCtxt` and invokes `do_mir_borrowck()` (compiler/rustc_borrowck/src/root_cx.rs:242).\n\nThe entry point calls `borrowck_collect_region_constraints` (compiler/rustc_borrowck/src/lib.rs:309), which:\n1. Builds the MIR body and replaces all regions with fresh inference variables via `replace_regions_in_mir` (compiler/rustc_borrowck/src/nll.rs:56)\n2. Creates a `BorrowSet` (compiler/rustc_borrowck/src/borrow_set.rs) that gathers all borrows in the MIR, handling two-phase borrows via the `insert_as_pending_if_two_phase` function (compiler/rustc_borrowck/src/borrow_set.rs:341). Two-phase borrows are tracked using the `TwoPhaseActivation` enum (compiler/rustc_borrowck/src/borrow_set.rs:66) which marks borrows as NotActivated until their activation location is found.\n3. Runs the type checker via `type_check::type_check()` to generate region constraints\n4. Invokes `compute_regions()` (compiler/rustc_borrowck/src/nll.rs:113) to perform NLL analysis\n\nPlace conflict detection happens during the type checking and dataflow analysis phases. The key functions are:\n- `places_conflict` (compiler/rustc_borrowck/src/places_conflict.rs:81) - top-level public API for checking if two places conflict\n- `borrow_conflicts_with_place` (compiler/rustc_borrowck/src/places_conflict.rs:104) - checks if a borrow conflicts with an access place\n- `place_components_conflict` (compiler/rustc_borrowck/src/places_conflict.rs:131) - recursively analyzes place projection components\n- `place_projection_conflict` (compiler/rustc_borrowck/src/places_conflict.rs:290) - determines overlap between individual projection elements\n\nLive range calculation is performed by `RegionInferenceContext::propagate_constraints()` (compiler/rustc_borrowck/src/region_infer/mod.rs:551). This method propagates region constraints through a DAG of strongly connected components (SCCs) to compute which regions must be live at which program locations. The region inference context is created in `compute_regions()` and tracks `LivenessValues` (compiler/rustc_borrowck/src/region_infer/values.rs) that record where regions must be live.\n\nThe `RegionInferenceContext::solve()` method (compiler/rustc_borrowck/src/region_infer/mod.rs:493) orchestrates the full region solving pipeline:\n1. Calls `propagate_constraints()` to compute region values based on outlives constraints\n2. Calls `check_type_tests()` to verify type outlives relationships\n3. Calls either `check_polonius_subset_errors()` or `check_universal_regions()` depending on the analysis mode\n\nTwo-phase borrow resolution is handled in the `BorrowSet` structure (compiler/rustc_borrowck/src/borrow_set.rs:16-34), which maintains:\n- `location_map`: Maps borrow locations to `BorrowData` (compiler/rustc_borrowck/src/borrow_set.rs:72)\n- `activation_map`: Maps activation locations to borrow indices\n- The `BorrowData` struct tracks the `activation_location` field (compiler/rustc_borrowck/src/borrow_set.rs:78) which stores where a two-phase borrow transitions from its reserved phase to active phase\n\nThe `insert_as_pending_if_two_phase()` function (compiler/rustc_borrowck/src/borrow_set.rs:341) marks two-phase borrows as NotActivated initially and inserts them into a pending activations map, allowing the borrow checker to defer conflict checking until the borrow is actually used (activated).\n\nThe overall MIR analysis flow integrates place conflict detection, live range computation via region propagation, and two-phase borrow handling to determine sound borrow relationships across the entire program."
